ownedRule.name: a metafacade can only generalize another metafacade

ownedComment.body: A metafacade can only generalize another metafacade.

specification.body: context Metafacade inv : generalization -> notEmpty() implies generalization.oclIsKindOf(Metafacade)

ownedRule.name: a metafacade can only specialize another metafacade

ownedComment.body: A metafacade can only specialize another metafacade.

specification.body: context Metafacade inv : specializations -> notEmpty() implies specializations -> forAll(oclIsKindOf(Metafacade))

ownedRule.name: a metafacade must either extend an existing metafacade or have a direct dependency to a metaclass

ownedComment.body: A metafacade must at the least, either extend an existing metafacade or have a direct dependency to a metaclass.

specification.body: context Metafacade inv: generalizations -> notEmpty() or sourceDependencies -> notEmpty()

A property related by memberEnd or its specializations to an association represents an end of the association. The type of the property is the type of the end of the association .Property represents a declared state of one or more instances in terms of a named relationship to a value or values. When a property is an association end, the value or values are related to the instance or instances at the other end(s) of the association.

A taxonomic relationship between a more general classifier and a more specific classifier. Each instance of the specific classifier is also an indirect instance of the general classifier. Thus, the specific classifier inherits the features of the more general classifier. A generalization relates a specific classifier to a more general classifier, and is owned by the specific classifier.

Represents an attribute on a classifier. UML2 maps both Attributes and AssociationEnds to Property. A property is a structural feature of a classifier that characterizes instances of the classifier. A property related by ownedAttribute to a classifier (other than an association) represents an attribute and might also represent an association end. It relates an instance of the class to a value or set of values of the type of the attribute. A property represents a set of instances that are owned by a containing classifier instance. Property represents a declared state of one or more instances in terms of a named relationship to a value or values. When a property is an attribute of a classifier, the value or values are related to the instance of the classifier by being held in slots of the instance. The range of valid values represented by the property can be controlled by setting the property's type.

A Classifier is a classification of instances - it describes a set of instances that have features in common. Can specify a generalization hierarchy by referencing its general classifiers. It may be a Class, DataType, PrimitiveType, Association, Collaboration, UseCase, etc. Can specify a generalization hierarchy by referencing its general classifiers. Has the capability to own collaboration uses. These collaboration uses link a collaboration with the classifier to give a description of the workings of the classifier. Classifier is defined to be a kind of templateable element so that a classifier can be parameterized. It is also defined to be a kind of parameterable element so that a classifier can be a formal template parameter.

State machines can be used to express the behavior of part of a system. Behavior is modeled as a traversal of a graph of state nodes interconnected by one or more joined transition arcs that are triggered by the dispatching of series of (event) occurrences. During this traversal, the state machine executes a series of activities associated with various elements of the state machine.

The first initial state (if any) found in this activity graph. Although technically many initial states per graph are allowed, it makes sense to have only one, for this reason we provide this property.
The first transition on the first initial state found for this activity graph.

Returns true if the model element has the specified stereotype. If the stereotype itself does not match, then a search will be made up the stereotype inheritance hierarchy, and if one of the stereotype's ancestors has a matching name this method will return true, false otherwise.
For example, if we have a certain stereotype called <<exception>> and a model element has a stereotype called <<applicationException>> which extends <<exception>>, when calling this method with 'stereotypeName' defined as 'exception' the method would return true since <<applicationException>> inherits from <<exception>>. If you want to check if the model element has the exact stereotype, then use the method 'hasExactStereotype' instead.

A representation of the model object 'Constraint'. A condition or restriction expressed in natural language text or in a machine readable language for the purpose of declaring some of the semantics of an element.
Condition or restriction expressed in natural language text or in a machine readable language for the purpose of declaring some of the semantics of an element.
Gets the 'body' or text of this constraint.

True if this constraint denotes an invariant. For example: 
   context LivingAnimal
   inv: alive = true
False otherwise.

True if this constraint denotes a precondition. For example: 
   context LivingAnimal::canFly()
   pre: hasWings = true
False otherwise.

True if this constraint denotes a postcondition. For example: 
   context LivingAnimal::getNumberOfLegs()
   post: numberOfLegs >= 0
False otherwise.

True if this constraint denotes a definition. For example: 
   context CustomerCard
   def: getTotalPoints(d: date) : Integer = transaction->select(date.isAfter(d)).points->sum()
False otherwise.

True if this constraint denotes a body expression. For example: 
   context CustomerCard:getTransaction(from:Date, until:Date)
   body: transactions->select(date.isAfter(from) and date.isBefore(until))
False otherwise.

Represents an operation on the server called by an action. Optionally may defer operations to the controller.

A special kind of state signifying that the enclosing region is completed. If the enclosing region is directly contained in a state machine and all other regions in the state machine also are completed, then it means that the entire state machine is completed.

Represents a UML template parameter. Exposes a parameterable element as a formal template parameter of a template. Only UML2 TemplateParameter inherits from ModelElement, so the UML14 implementation cannot extend ModelElement. UML14 TemplateParameter.parameter inherits from Parameter.
Return the default element for the template parameter
Returns the parameter value for the template parameter. In andromda, parameter and template parameter functionality are combined for simplicity.

get + capitalized parameter name

The ModelElement that owns this parameter. For UML14, the classifier package. For UML2, the Classifier.

Gets the documentation for the model element, The indent argument is prefixed to each line. By default this method wraps lines after 64 characters. This method is equivalent to getDocumentation(indent, 64).
Specifies the amount to indent by.

This method returns the documentation for this model element, with the lines wrapped after the specified number of characters, values of less than 1 will indicate no line wrapping is required. A user-defined data value for an enumeration.
Returns the value of this enumeration literal, by default the value is the same as the name.
Gets the name of the enumeration literal (if the "modelName" flag is true, then the actual name of the literal in the model is returned - otherwise the name that has any masking applied).

Gets the value of the enumeration literal (if the "modelValue" flag is true, then the actual value of the literal in the model is returned - otherwise the value that has any masking applied is returned).

UML2: Returns the value of the 'Is Derived' attribute. The default value is "false". If isDerived is true, the value of the attribute is derived from information elsewhere. Specifies whether the Property is derived, i.e., whether its value or values can be computed from other information.

UML2: Determines whether this association is a binary association, i.e. whether it has exactly two member ends. UML2 allows association classes in the association itself (many2many with association attributes). Default=true: only two member ends.
The first association end.
The second association end.
Gets the association ends belonging to this association.
A front-end parameter is a parameter passed between front-end action states.
Indicates whether or not this parameter is an argument of a controller operation.
Indicates if this parameter is contained in a "front-end" use case.
Indicates whether or not this is an action parameter or not.
Indicates whether or not this parameter represents a table.

All the columns for this parameter if it represents a table variable. If a column is linked by an event (action) a FrontEndParameter instance is included in the return value, otherwise a plain String representing the column name.

The action to which this parameter belongs (if it belongs to an action), otherwise it returns null.

An action is a named element that is the fundamental unit of executable functionality. The execution of an action represents some transformation or processing in the modeled system, be it a computer system or otherwise. An action represents a single step within an activity, that is, one that is not further decomposed within the activity. An action has pre- and post-conditions.
If this action is located on an action state, this will represent that state.
If this action is located on a transition, this represents that transition.
Represents a view within a front end application.
True if this element carries the FrontEndView stereotype.
All tables belonging to the front end view.
All parameters for each action going out of this view.
All actions that can be triggered on this view.
All fields from all forms on the given view.
All those variables that will be present as variables in the target view. These are the trigger parameters on the incoming transitions.
The use-case of which this view is a member.
Represents an argument to an operation. All parameters except for the return parameter.
The specification of a set of actions performed by a system, which yields an observable result that is, typically, of value for one or more actors or other stakeholders of the system.
The extend instances related to this use-case.
The included instances related to this use-case.
The extension points related to this use-case.
The first activity graph directly owned by this use-case.

Captures a view of a physical system. It is an abstraction of the physical system, with a certain purpose. This purpose determines what is to be included in the model and what is irrelevant. Return all Classes and Datatypes belonging to this model.

Return all Actors belonging to this model.
Return all UseCases belonging to this model.

A representation of the model object 'Instance Specification'. Represents an instance in a modeled system. Has the capability of being a deployment target in a deployment relationship, in the case that it is an instance of a node. Has the capability of being a deployed artifact, if it is an instance of an artifact.

All slots for this instance, this includes the ones that map onto attributes and the ones that map onto association ends. In fact, this feature holds the collection of both InstanceFacade.attributeLinks and InstanceFacade.linkEnds.
Those slots that map onto association ends.

A representation of the model object 'Activity'. The specification of parameterized behavior as the coordinated sequencing of subordinate units whose individual elements are actions.
The operation called by this event.
The operations of this call event facade. For UML 1.4 only one operation will be present, for UML2, there can be more than one present.
A representation of the model object 'Region'. An orthogonal part of either a composite state or a state machine. It contains states and transitions.
All vertices enveloped by this partition.

A representation of the model object 'Instance Specification'. Represents an instance in a modeled system. Has the capability of being a deployment target in a deployment relationship, in the case that it is an instance of a node. Has the capability of being a deployed artifact, if it is an instance of an artifact.
The two links ends owned by this link.
Represents the activity graph describing the details of a presentation tier or "front end" use case.
True if this element is contained in a FrontEndUseCase.
The controller context for this activity graph. This controller can be the target of deferrable events in the action states and transitions in this graph.
This is the initial action encountered in this activity graph. This is the one and only transition coming out of the initial state.

A representation of the model object 'Call Operation Action'. An action that transmits an operation call request to the target object, where it may cause the invocation of associated behavior. The argument values of the action are available to the execution of the invoked behavior. If the action is marked synchronous, the execution of the call operation action waits until the execution of the invoked behavior completes and a reply transmission is returned to the caller; otherwise execution of the action is complete when the invocation of the operation is established and the execution of the invoked operation proceeds concurrently with the execution of the calling behavior. Any values returned as part of the reply transmission are put on the result output pins of the call operation action. Upon receipt of the reply transmission, execution of the call operation action is complete.
The operation called by this action.

Used to group elements, and provides a namespace for the grouped elements. A package can have one or more profile applications to indicate which profiles have been applied. Because a profile is a package, it is possible to apply a profile not only to packages, but also to profiles. Package specializes TemplateableElement and PackageableElement specializes ParameterableElement to specify that a package can be used as a template and a PackageableElement as a template parameter.
The Entity table prefix to be used for this package.
Returns all classes in this package
Gets all the model elements belonging to the root package.
returns all packages belonging to this package.
The elements directly found in this package.
Finds the model element with the given 'fullyQualifiedName', or returns null if one can't be found with that name.
The fully qualified name of the model element to find.

A state models a situation during which some (usually implicit) invariant condition holds. The states of protocol state machines are exposed to the users of their context classifiers. A protocol state represents an exposed stable situation of its context classifier: when an instance of the classifier is not processing any operation, users of this instance can always know its state configuration.
The entry action for this action state (if any).
Represents the model object 'Template Parameter Substitution'. Relates the actual parameter(s) to a formal template parameter as part of a template binding.
Represents an operation modeled on a controller.
Indicates if the owner of this operation is a controller.

For each front-end controller operation argument there must exist a form field for each action deferring to that operation. This form field must carry the same name and must be of the same type. True if this is the case, false otherwise.
The activity graph in which this controller operation is used.

All those actions that contain at least one front-end action state that is deferring to this operation.
Represents a UML Destination for incoming/outgoing messages.
Encapsulates a pseudostate and provides specific front-end services. This pseudostate can be a decision point, junction or initial state.
Indicates if this "front-end" pseudo date is contained within a "front-end" use case.
The actions that pass through this pseudo state.
A signature containing the template parameters for the templated element (Class, operation, property, etc). A template signature bundles the set of formal template parameters for a templated element.
The Class which is templated.

State machines can be used to express the behavior of part of a system. Behavior is modeled as a traversal of a graph of state nodes interconnected by one or more joined transition arcs that are triggered by the dispatching of series of (event) occurrences. During this traversal, the state machine executes a series of activities associated with various elements of the state machine. Not implmented for UML2.
Represents an attribute of an entity.
The length of the column that persists this entity attribute.
The name of the table column to which this entity is mapped.
The PIM to language specific mappings for JDBC.
The JDBC type for this entity attribute.
The SQL mappings (i.e. the mappings which provide PIM to SQL mappings).
The SQL type for this attribute.
True if this attribute is an identifier for its entity.

Indicates this attribute should be ignored by the persistence layer.
The name of the unique-key that this unique attribute belongs
Represents a service.
References to all services to which this service has a dependency.

All messaging destinations that belong to this service and all decendent services.
All messaging destinations available to this service.
References to all entities to which this service has a dependency.
All roles associated with the service, this includes both roles that have access to the entire service, and any roles that have access to a single operation.
Returns a collection of all entities this service and its ancestors have a relation to.
The roles of the service, these are the actor's that can access this service.
Represents an enumeration. A data type whose values are enumerated in the model as enumeration literals. May also be a Classifier with Stereotype Enumeration.
The 'from' operation signature. This is the signature that takes the actual literal value and allows a new enumeration to be constructed.
The 'from' operation name. This is the name of the operation that takes the actual literal value and allows a new enumeration to be constructed.
Indicates whether the enumeration must be generated using a Java 5 type-safe enum or a traditional enumeration-pattern class.
The type of the enumeration's literals.
The enumeration member variables.
This enumeration's literals.

Specification of an argument used to pass information into or out of an invocation of a behavioral feature. Parameters are allowed to be treated as connectable elements. Parameters have support for streaming, exceptions, and parameter sets.
Indicates if the default value is present.
The name to use for accessors getting this parameter from a bean.
Fully Qualified TypeName, determined in part by multiplicity (for UML2). For UML14, same as getterName.
Fully Qualified implementation class of TypeName, determined in part by multiplicity (for UML2). If upper multiplicity =1, same as getterSetterTypeName.
Whether or not this parameter is considered required (i.e must a non-empty value).
Whether or not this parameter represents a return parameter.
The name to use for accessors getting this parameter in a bean.
True if this parameter is readable, aka an in-parameter, or this feature is unspecified.

the upper value of the multiplicity (will be -1 for *) -only applicable for UML2

If Parameter type isMany (UML2), is the parameter unique within the Collection. Unique+Sorted determines pareter implementation type. For UML14, always false.
UML2 Only: Is parameter ordered within the Collection type. Ordered+Unique determines the implementation Collection Type. For UML14, always false.
If upper>1 or upper==unlimited. Only applies to UML2. For UML14, always false.
UML2: Returns the value of the 'Is Exception' attribute. The default value is "false". Tells whether an output parameter may emit a value to the exclusion of the other outputs.

UML2: A representation of the literals of the enumeration 'Parameter Effect Kind': CREATE, READ, UPDATE, DELETE. The datatype ParameterEffectKind is an enumeration that indicates the effect of a behavior on values passed in or out of its parameters.
If this parameter is located on an event, this will represent that event.
If this parameter is located on an operation, this will represent that operation.

A model element that has both association and class properties. An AssociationClass can be seen as an association that also has class properties, or as a class that also has association properties. It not only connects a set of classifiers but also defines a set of features that belong to the relationship itself and not to any of the classifiers.
The association ends visible to this association class.
Represents a use case used in the "front end" of an application.
True if this use-case is the entry point to the front end.
Indicates if this use case is "secured". This is true when there is at least one role associated to it.
The final states linking to this use case
All roles that directly or indirectly related to any "front-end" use cases.
Returns all roles that are directly and indirectly associated to this use-case.
Returns the controller for this use-case.
All views that are part of this use case.
The actions for this use-case. This will include the initial action to start the use-case.
Returns all struts use-cases in this "front end" application.
The first view of this use case, this may actually return a view of another use case if the first is found by traveling through the final state.
Returns the activity graph describing this use-case in more detail.
The variables for all views in this use-case. A parameter qualifies to be a variable when it explicitely and directly receives it via an action.
Represents a role a user may play within a system. Provides access to things such as services and service operations.
Indicates if the necessary references are present for the Role. This include any references to a service, service operation or use case.
Gets the namespace to which this model element belongs.

Models a situation during which some (usually implicit) invariant condition holds. The states of protocol state machines are exposed to the users of their context classifiers. A protocol state represents an exposed stable situation of its context classifier: when an instance of the classifier is not processing any operation, users of this instance can always know its state configuration.
Events to which is being deferred in this action state.
A representation of the model object 'Vertex'. An abstraction of a node in a state machine graph. In general, it can be the source or destination of any number of transitions.
The partition (if any) to which this vertex belongs.
An element in a model that contains a set of named elements that can be identified by name.
Gets the model elements which this namespace owns.

Can be an AttributeLinkImpl or LinkEndImpl. A representation of the model object 'Slot'. A slot specifies that an entity modeled by an instance specification has a value or values for a specific structural feature.
The link owning this link end.
The instances this link end is attached too. A link can have many instance values when its defining feature is an association end with a 'many' multiplicity.

ownedRule.name: classifier must have a name

ownedComment.body: Each classifier must have a non-empty name.

ownedRule.name: parameter needs a type

ownedComment.body: Each parameter needs a type, you cannot leave the type unspecified.

specification.body: context ParameterFacade inv: return = false implies type.name->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: association end needs a type

ownedComment.body: Each association end needs a type, you cannot leave the type unspecified.

ownedRule.name: attribute needs a type

ownedComment.body: Each attribute needs a type, you cannot leave the type unspecified.

ownedRule.name: operation needs a return type

ownedComment.body: Each operation needs a return type, you cannot leave the type unspecified, even if you want void you'll need to explicitly specify it.

ownedRule.name: entity must have at least one primary key

ownedComment.body: Each entity must have at least one identifier defined.

ownedRule.name: attribute must have a name

ownedComment.body: Each attribute must have a non-empty name.

ownedRule.name: non return type parameters must be named

ownedComment.body: Each parameter that is NOT a return parameter must have a non-empty name.

specification.body: context ParameterFacade inv: return = false implies name -> notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: operation must have a name

ownedComment.body: Each operation must have a non-empty name.

ownedRule.name: valid foreign identifiers.

ownedComment.body: Only ONE association end on an entity can be flagged as having a foreign identifier at any given time. It also MUST be the child end (the other side is flagged as having composite aggregation) of a one-to-one association.

specification.body: context EntityAssociationEndFacade inv : foreignIdentifier implies (one2One and child and type.associationEnds -> one (foreignIdentifier))

ownedRule.name: attribute names must be unique

ownedComment.body: Each attribute on an element must have a unique name.

ownedRule.name: entity must have all public attributes

ownedComment.body: All attributes on an entity must have a public visibility.

ownedRule.name: entity must have public associations

ownedComment.body: All navigable connecting association ends must have a public visibility.

specification.body: context Entity inv : associationEnds -> forAll(otherEnd.navigable implies otherEnd.visibility = 'public')

ownedRule.name: entities can only generalize other entities

ownedComment.body: An entity can only generalize another entity.

specification.body: context Entity inv : generalization -> notEmpty() implies generalization.oclIsKindOf(Entity)

ownedRule.name: a service can only generalize another service

ownedComment.body: A service can only generalize another service.

specification.body: context Service inv : generalization -> notEmpty() implies generalization.oclIsKindOf(Service)

ownedRule.name: entities can only specialize other entites

ownedComment.body: An entity can only specialize another entity.

specification.body: context Entity inv : specializations -> notEmpty() implies specializations -> forAll(oclIsKindOf(Entity))

ownedRule.name: services can only specialize other service

ownedComment.body: A service can only specialize another service.

specification.body: context ServiceFacade inv : specializations -> notEmpty() implies specializations -> forAll(oclIsKindOf(Service))

ownedRule.name: enumerations must have at least one literal value

ownedComment.body: An enumeration must have at least one literal modeled.

ownedRule.name: association end names must be unique

ownedComment.body: The name of each navigable connecting association end must be unique.

ownedRule.name: each usecase needs one and only one graph

ownedComment.body: Each use-case needs one and only one activity graph.

ownedRule.name: one and only one usecase must be a FrontEndApplication

ownedComment.body: One and only one use-case must be marked as the application entry use-case. Currently this is done by adding the FrontEndApplication stereotype to it.

ownedRule.name: non-empty unique usecase name

ownedComment.body: Each use-case must have a non-empty name that is unique among all use-cases.

specification.body: context FrontEndUseCase inv: name->notEmpty() and model.allUseCases->isUnique(name)

ownedRule.name: no more than one controller per package

ownedComment.body: In order to avoid possible naming collisions at most one controller per package is allowed. It is recommended to refactor your model.

ownedRule.name: no more than one usecase per package

ownedComment.body: In order to avoid possible naming collisions at most one FrontEndUseCase per package is allowed. It is recommended to refactor your model.

ownedRule.name: non-empty unique role name

ownedComment.body: Each role must have a non-empty name that is unique among all other roles.

specification.body: context Role inv: name->notEmpty() and model.allActors->isUnique(name)

ownedRule.name: each front-end action state must have a name

ownedComment.body: A "front-end" action state must have a non-empty name.

ownedRule.name: front-end action states can have at most one outgoing transition

ownedComment.body: A "front-end" action state needs at most one outgoing transition that is not an exception-transition.

specification.body: context FrontEndActionState inv: serverSide implies (exceptions->size() + 1 = outgoings->size() or exceptions->size() = outgoings->size())

ownedRule.name: unique view name per usecase

ownedComment.body: Each name of a view action state must be unique in the namespace of a front-end use-case.

ownedRule.name: each front end view action requires a unique name (unique in the scope of that view)

ownedComment.body: Each action going out of a frontend view must have a unique name in the scope of that view.

ownedRule.name: view variables must have unique names

ownedComment.body: Each view-variable should have a unique name within the context of a view.

ownedRule.name: front-end views cannot defer operations

ownedComment.body: Views cannot defer to operations. All deferrable events modeled on a front-end view will be ignored.

ownedRule.name: all arguments need an event parameter

ownedComment.body: For each controller operation argument there must exist a parameter for each action deferring to that operation. This parameter must carry the same name and must be of the same type.

ownedRule.name: the operation name may not be the same as the use-case name

ownedComment.body: It is not allowed to give a controller operation the same name as the use-case for which it is defined, please either rename your operation or your use-case.

ownedRule.name: parameters must be unique

ownedComment.body: Each front-end action parameter must have a unique name.

ownedRule.name: each action going out of a front-end view must be unique

ownedComment.body: Each view must contain actions which each have a unique name, this view has actions with duplicate names.

ownedRule.name: each action must carry a trigger

ownedComment.body: Each action transition coming out of a view must have a trigger (the name is sufficient), it is recommended to add a trigger of type 'signal'.

specification.body: context FrontEndAction inv: exitingView implies triggerPresent

ownedRule.name: each front-end use-case needs to be in a package

ownedComment.body: Each front-end use-case is required to be modeled in a package, doing otherwise will result in uncompileable code due to filename collisions.

ownedRule.name: front-end controllers need a package

ownedComment.body: Each front-end controller is required to be modeled in a package, doing otherwise will result in uncompileable code due to filename collisions.

ownedRule.name: source dependencies must be unique

ownedComment.body: Each dependency going out a of an element must have a unique name.

ownedRule.name: primitive attribute must be required

ownedComment.body: Primitive attributes must have a multiplicity lower bound > 0 (must be required). Use a wrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

ownedRule.name: primitive attribute cannot be used in Collection

ownedComment.body: Primitive attributes cannot be used in Collections (multiplicity > 1). Use the wrapped type instead.

specification.body: context AttributeFacade inv: type.primitive implies (many = false)

ownedRule.name: primitive parameter cannot be used in Collection

ownedComment.body: Primitive parameters cannot be used in Collections (multiplicity > 1). Use the wrapped type instead.

specification.body: context ParameterFacade inv: type.primitive implies (many = false)

ownedRule.name: primitive parameter must be required

ownedComment.body: Primitive operation parameters must have a multiplicity lower bound > 0 (must be required). Use a wrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

ownedRule.name: primitive operation return cannot be used in a Collection

ownedComment.body: Primitive return parameters cannot be used in Collections (multiplicity > 1). Use the wrapped type or Array type instead.

specification.body: context OperationFacade inv: returnParameter.type.primitive implies (many = false)

ownedRule.name: wrapped primitive parameter should not be required

ownedComment.body: Wrapped primitive operation parameters must have a multiplicity lower bound = 0 (must be optional). Use the unwrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

specification.body: context ParameterFacade inv: type.wrappedPrimitive and many = false implies (lower = 0)

ownedRule.name: wrapped primitive operation return should not be required

ownedComment.body: Wrapped primitive operation return must have a multiplicity lower bound = 0 (must be optional). Use the unwrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

specification.body: context OperationFacade inv: returnParameter.type.wrappedPrimitive and many = false implies (lower = 0)

ownedRule.name: primitive operation return must be required

ownedComment.body: Primitive operation return types must have a multiplicity lower bound > 0 (must be required). Use a wrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

ownedRule.name: wrapped primitive attribute should not be required

ownedComment.body: Wrapped primitive attributes must have a multiplicity lower bound = 0 (must be optional). Use the unwrapped type, or change the multiplicity.

specification.body: context AttributeFacade inv: type.wrappedPrimitive and many = false implies (lower = 0)

ownedRule.name: operation multiplicity must match return parameter multiplicity

ownedComment.body: Operation return parameter with multiplicity greater than 1 must match the operation multiplicity greater than 1.

ownedRule.name: name cannot be a reserved word

ownedComment.body: Model Element name cannot be a reserved word

ownedRule.name: template parameter type must be specified

ownedComment.body: Template Parameter type must be specified.

ownedRule.name: name must be a valid identifier

ownedComment.body: Model Element name cannot be a reserved word
Represents a "front-end" action. An action is some action that is taken when a front-end even occurs.

All the transitions coming out of decision points. These transitions should all carry guards.
All action forwards for this foward. Each action forward either calls a view or another use-case (which is essentially an action).
The StateVertex (FrontEndView or PseudostateFacade) on which this action can be triggered.

All parameters sent by this "front-end" action.
All action states visited by this action.
Form fields for this action. Form fields are those parameters that can be altered by the user on a corresponding view at runtime.
All views that can be possibly targetted by triggering this action.
The controller operations to which this action defers, the order is preserved.
Finds the parameter on this action having the given name, if no parameter is found, null is returned instead.
The name of the parameter to find on the owner action.
Identifies a point in the behavior of a use case where that behavior can be extended by the behavior of some other (extending) use case, as specified by an extend relationship.
A representation of the model object 'Directed Relationship'.Represents a relationship between a collection of source model elements and a collection of target model elements, a dependency/reference.
The "getter" name for this dependency.
The "setter" name for this dependency.
The source element of this dependency.
Gets the element to which the dependencies belong.
Whether or not this attribute should be displayed.
Whether or not this attribute can be read in a call isolated from the rest (for example when downloading binary fields).
Reprsents an operation of a service.
Whether or not this operation represents an "incoming" message operation (i.e. it receives messages from Queues or Topics).
Whether or not this service operation represents an "outgoing" messaging operation (i.e. it sends messages to Queues or Topics).
Whether or not this is operation accepts incoming or outgoing messages.

State machines can be used to express the behavior of part of a system. Behavior is modeled as a traversal of a graph of state nodes interconnected by one or more joined transition arcs that are triggered by the dispatching of series of (event) occurrences. During this traversal, the state machine executes a series of activities associated with various elements of the state machine.
